{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17488430","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17488430"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T03:41:50+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T03:41:50+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"442"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"442","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/442"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.02,0.05,0.32,0.05,0.55]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"442"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"96871"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"442","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/442"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"442"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79486"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"36"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1139"},{"type":"tags","id":"2115"},{"type":"tags","id":"2924"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"3719"},{"type":"contributions","id":"4120"},{"type":"contributions","id":"33215"},{"type":"contributions","id":"39150"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"96871","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/96871"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 62-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic following a CT scan of the abdomen performed as part of the work-up for suspected diverticulitis. Apart from confirming the presence of sigmoid diverticulae, the CT also shows a 3mm stone in the upper calyx of the right kidney. He has a medical history of hypertension. His only regular medicine is amlodipine 5mg daily. He has never had any urinary symptoms. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Abdominal examination is unremarkable with no flank tenderness. Urinalysis shows no blood, leucocytes, or nitrites. Investigations reveal normal serum biochemistry, including renal function.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate management plan?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Percutaneous nephrolithotomy","Extracorporeal shockwave lithotripsy","Further imaging in one year","Tamsulosin and ibuprofen","Reassurance with no further follow-up"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient has an incidentally discovered small (3mm) asymptomatic renal calculus. The natural history of small renal calculi is that approximately 10-15% of people develop symptomatic episodes each year, with intervention rates of around 25% at three years in retrospective studies.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFurther imaging in one year\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate management for this patient. While no immediate intervention is required for this small, asymptomatic stone, surveillance is recommended to monitor for growth or development of symptoms. There are no standardised follow-up regimens, but the principles include limiting radiation exposure where possible, and ultrasound is often a reasonable first line imaging modality for follow up with yearly imaging for two years and, if stable, two-yearly imaging thereafter.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EReassurance with no further follow-up\u003C/strong\u003E would be inappropriate as this stone does need to be kept under surveillance. Without monitoring, the stone could grow or become symptomatic without the patient being aware of potential complications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETamsulosin and ibuprofen\u003C/strong\u003E are medications used in medical expulsive therapy (MET) which may improve the passage of ureteric stones and limit the use of narcotics for pain relief. This therapy is not indicated for calyceal stones that are not causing obstruction or symptoms.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EExtracorporeal shockwave lithotripsy\u003C/strong\u003E can be used to manage calculi in the renal pelvis or calyces, particularly for stones \u0026lt;15mm. While this could be an option for a patient not wanting to proceed with surveillance, it represents unnecessary intervention for an asymptomatic 3mm stone with its associated risks and costs.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPercutaneous nephrolithotomy\u003C/strong\u003E is an invasive surgical procedure typically reserved for large (\u0026gt;2cm) or complex renal stones. This approach would be excessively invasive for a small, asymptomatic 3mm calyceal stone and carries significant risks including bleeding, infection, and injury to surrounding structures.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EFactors that may prompt intervention for an asymptomatic renal stone include: stone \u0026gt;5mm, stone growing in size, single kidney, occupational requirements (need to be stone-free, e.g., pilot, military), and recurrent urinary tract infections. None of these factors is present for this patient, making surveillance the most appropriate approach.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["For small (\u003C5mm) asymptomatic renal calculi with no strong indications or patient preference for treatment, follow-up imaging in 1 year is recommended.","Approximately 10-15% of people with asymptomatic renal calculi develop symptomatic episodes each year.","Indications for intervention in asymptomatic renal stones include stones \u003E5mm, growing stones, single kidney, occupational requirements, and recurrent urinary tract infections."],"references":["Sewell J, Katz D, Shoshany O, Love C. Urolithiasis \u2013 Ten things every general practitioner should know. Australian Family Physician. 2017;46:648-52. Available at: https://www.racgp.org.au/afp/2017/september/urolithiasis","T\u00fcrk C, Pet\u0159\u00edk A, Sarica K, Seitz C, Skolarikos A, Straub M, et al. EAU Guidelines on Diagnosis and Conservative Management of Urolithiasis. (1873-7560 (Electronic)). Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/26318710/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79486"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"442"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79486","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/79486"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-04-03T09:34:37+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-04-03T09:34:37+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"442"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"96871"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"36","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/36"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd43","name":"Urology","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"